Predicting Future Traffic Volume¶

Introduction:

This data set contains hourly information regarding traffic volume and weather conditions on a highway between Minneapolis and St. Paul, Minnesota. The data set can be obtained at: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Metro+Interstate+Traffic+Volume. The goal of this project is to apply deep learning to do time series forecasting. Specifically, given a 6-hour input window, this project will attempt to predict the traffic volume 2 hours/time steps into the future using several different neural networks.

Import libraries and read in file:

Split the Data into Training, Validation, and Test sets:

In [15]:
train = traffic[0:33205]
validation = traffic[33205:43204]
test = traffic[43204::]  # last 5,000 observations for test set

Normalize the Data:

  • Here, the feature variables must be normalized separately from the target variable. This way, it will be much easier to denormalize the target predictions for the test set later on.
In [16]:
feat_columns = ['temp', 'rain_1h', 'snow_1h', 'clouds_all', 'month', 'day_of_week', 'hour']

feat_transformer = MinMaxScaler()
traf_transformer = MinMaxScaler()

feat_transformer = feat_transformer.fit(train[feat_columns].to_numpy())
traf_transformer = traf_transformer.fit(train[['traffic_volume']])

train.loc[:, feat_columns] = feat_transformer.transform(train[feat_columns].to_numpy())
train['traffic_volume'] = traf_transformer.transform(train[['traffic_volume']])

validation.loc[:, feat_columns] = feat_transformer.transform(validation[feat_columns].to_numpy())
validation['traffic_volume'] = traf_transformer.transform(validation[['traffic_volume']])

test.loc[:, feat_columns] = feat_transformer.transform(test[feat_columns].to_numpy())
test['traffic_volume'] = traf_transformer.transform(test[['traffic_volume']])

Create X and Y Datasets:

In [17]:
# create X and Y from training set:
y_train = train['traffic_volume']
x_train = train.drop(['traffic_volume'], axis=1)

# create X and Y from validation set:
y_val = validation['traffic_volume']
x_val = validation.drop(['traffic_volume'], axis =1)

# create X and Y from test set:
y_test = test['traffic_volume']
x_test = test.drop(['traffic_volume'], axis =1)

Create Function to Transform Datasets into Proper Format for TensorFlow Keras:

  • function to iterate through dataset based on time steps/window (6 hours) and target step size (2 hours into the future)
  • returns arrays in format: [samples, timesteps, features] and [samples, ] for X and Y, respectively
In [18]:
def create_dataset(X, y, time_step = 6, target_step = 2):
  Xs, ys = [], []  # empty lists
  for i in range(len(X) - (time_step + target_step)): # iterate through range based on length of dataset and time step & target step sizes -JL
    dist = X.iloc[i: (i + time_step)].to_numpy() # distance of time step/window -JL
    Xs.append(dist)
    ys.append(y.iloc[i + time_step + target_step]) # target index
  return np.array(Xs), np.array(ys)

Transform Training, Validation, and Test Datasets into [samples, timesteps, features] and [samples, ] formats for TensorFlow Keras:

In [19]:
X_train, Y_train = create_dataset(x_train, y_train, 6, 2)

X_val, Y_val = create_dataset(x_val, y_val, 6, 2)

X_test, Y_test = create_dataset(x_test, y_test, 6, 2)

Combine CNN with RNN¶

In [153]:
model = models.Sequential()
model.add(layers.Conv1D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, strides =1, padding = 'same', activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train.shape[1], X_train.shape[2])))
model.add(layers.LSTM(64))
model.add(layers.Dense(32, activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.Dense(1, activation = 'relu'))
In [154]:
model.compile(optimizer='adam',
              loss= 'mean_absolute_error')
In [155]:
history = model.fit(X_train, Y_train, epochs=30,
                    validation_data=(X_val, Y_val), shuffle = False)
